post_text:
Yesterday, Governor Grisham and Secretary Stewart had a press conference to provide an update on school reopening in New Mexico.

The original goal of the Governor’s office was to start phasing students back to school starting at the Elementary level after Labor Day using the hybrid learning model. Due to the recent increase in cases in southeast NM, the phase in for Chaves County will be delayed until the COVID numbers improve.

Attached is the “green map” that was used in the press conference. Only schools located in the counties that are green will be allowed to start phasing students back at the Elementary level using the hybrid model after Labor Day. Schools in counties that are yellow or red must wait until the COVID numbers improve.

As soon as the status of Chaves County changes, we will let everyone know. Until then we continue educating our students via the remote/online learning model.

Meal delivery will resume via daily bus routes on Monday August 24! Please be at your bus stops at regular pick up / drop off times to receive a meal.

During remote learning, Dexter Schools will provide meals to our Dexter Students via bus routes or through Grab & Go meals that can be picked up at the High School cafeteria.

MEAL DELIVERY: Breakfast meals will be delivered to the regular bus stops each morning and lunch meals will be delivered each afternoon. If your Dexter student would like a free breakfast or lunch, please have them waiting at their assigned bus stop at their regular pickup and drop off times Monday through Friday.

MEAL PICKUP: Grab & Go meals will be available in front of the High School cafeteria Monday through Friday. Breakfast, 8:00 – 9:00; Lunch, 2:00 – 3:00.

~~Las comidas de los estudiantes comenzarán el lunes 10 de agosto~~

Durante el aprendizaje remoto, las escuelas de Dexter proporcionarán comidas a nuestros estudiantes de Dexter a través de rutas de autobús o comidas Agarrar y Llevar que se pueden recoger en la cafetería de la escuela secundaria.

ENTREGA DE COMIDAS: Las comidas del desayuno se entregarán a las paradas de autobús regulares cada mañana y las comidas del lonche se entregarán cada tarde. Si su estudiante de Dexter desea un desayuno y lonche gratis, pídales que esperen en la parada de autobús asignada en su horario regular de recogida y entrega de lunes a viernes.

RECOGIDA DE COMIDAS: Comidas de Agarrar y Llevar estarán disponibles en frente de la cafetería de la escuela preparatoria de lunes a viernes. Desayuno, 8:00 - 9:00; Lonche, 2:00 - 3:00.

Las comidas solo están disponibles para los estudiantes de Dexter. Las comidas de los estudiantes comenzarán el lunes 10 de agosto.

Atención familias: Sabemos que tiene preguntas sobre el regreso a la escuela y lo más importante para muchos es el tema del cuidado infantil durante los modelos de aprendizaje híbrido y a distancia. En orden a preparar y ofrecer adecuadamente recursos, apoyos y programación que satisfagan las necesidades de nuestra comunidad, PED está buscando su opinión. Por favor complete la Encuesta de cuidado infantil de NM en el siguiente enlace.

La encuesta hará una serie de preguntas sobre las necesidades de su familia en la entrada del nuevo año escolar y no debería tomar más de 10-15 minutos.

💙🏀🏀

I encourage each of you to go for runs while dribbling, and shoot as often as you can. Ball handling is the key!

The most recent update from NMAA

YOUTUBE.COM
Interview with NMAA Executive Director Sally Marquez May 4 2020

post_text:
Dexter Schools is so very fortunate to have fantastic teachers educating our students each day, teachers who are dedicated and devoted to their students and their learning.

The past few weeks have resulted in major changes in how they do their jobs, but they all stepped up, demonstrated the flexibility to change and made sure the education of their students has not stopped or even slowed down. It has been incredible to witness the way everyone has adapted to a difficult situation. Their presence at school, in their buildings and in their classrooms is missed every day. We can’t wait until everyone is back on-site working face-to-face with our children. Until then, we know they will keep up the great work that they are doing from home!

Thank you for all that you do for our students! Stay safe and healthy.
text:
Dexter Schools is so very fortunate to have fantastic teachers educating our students each day, teachers who are dedicated and devoted to their students and their learning.

The past few weeks have resulted in major changes in how they do their jobs, but they all stepped up, demonstrated the flexibility to change and made sure the education of their students has not stopped or even slowed down. It has been incredible to witness the way everyone has adapted to a difficult situation. Their presence at school, in their buildings and in their classrooms is missed every day. We can’t wait until everyone is back on-site working face-to-face with our children. Until then, we know they will keep up the great work that they are doing from home!

Thank you for all that you do for our students! Stay safe and healthy.

post_text: Children’s mental health thrives or struggles within the context of family, community, and culture. As families respond to changes in the world and health and financial stressors, their children’s well-being is also impacted. Toxic stress and trauma are known risk factors of child maltreatment and families need all of the additional supports available. Now more than ever, we need to intentionally support the mental health of people of all ages. Here are some FREE, well-organized resources from the leading national experts in Infant Mental Health to promote infant and child mental health. On the same page you’ll find a video with tips for families during the time of the coronavirus.

will sign an Executive Order to direct New Mexico public education to shift to a learn-at-home model as schools remain closed for the rest of the academic year. This decision, which was made in consultation with the New Mexico Public Education Department and the New Mexico Department of Health, is part of a two-pronged plan to protect New Mexicans from COVID-19 and ensure that children are protected, fed and educated and that families are supported through this crisis.

La nueva orden de emergencia de salud pública, cual fue anunciada ayer por la gobernadora, no afecta el periodo de cierre de escuelas públicas. Sin embargo, es probable que el cierre sea prolongado. Reconocemos que el público está esperando ansiosamente información actualizada y es nuestra intención dar un aviso lo más pronto posible para que puedan hacer planes. Durante una conferencia de prensa ayer, la gobernadora Michelle Lujan Grisham dijo lo siguiente: "Estamos trabajando con el gobierno federal [para saber] – que exenciones deben estar en orden, que hacemos sobre las graduaciones, que hacemos con las solicitudes universitarias, que hacemos con el apoyo y aprendizaje de educación a distancia, cómo asegurarnos que cada estudiante tiene el mismo acceso a su nivel de aprendizaje, cual es un requisito importante para los estados rurales como este." Anticipamos hacer un anuncio dentro de esta semana o a principios de la próxima semana.

shared_text:
New Mexico Public Education Department
March 24 at 9:33 AM ·

The new Public Health Order issued yesterday does not affect the Public School Closure Period, but an extended closure is likely. We know that you are eagerly awaiting an update and it is our intention to give you as much notice as possible to make plans. As Governor Michelle Lujan Grisham said during the press conference yesterday, "We are working with the federal government-- what waivers need to be in place, what we do about graduations, what we do about college applications, what we do about distance learning and support, how can we assure every student has the same access to that level of learning, which is an important requirement for rural states like this one." We anticipate making an announcement later this week or early next week.

post_text:
Per Governor Michelle Lujan-Grisham, all NM schools will be closed starting Monday, March 16 through Friday, April 3 to help prevent the spread of the coronavirus.

Classes are scheduled to resume on Monday, April 6.

During this time, it is important that everyone practice “social isolation” in order to prevent the spread of this virus. Social isolation means remaining out of congregate settings (i.e., malls, movie theaters, special events, etc.), avoiding mass gatherings, and maintaining distance (approximately 6 feet) from others when possible.

Per the Governor’s press conference, the following hotline numbers will be available if you have coronavirus questions in the following areas:

Health Related Questions – 1-855-600-3453
Miscellaneous Questions – 1-833-551-0518

shared_text:
Lt. Governor Howie Morales is with Howie Morales.
March 12 at 4:16 PM ·

New Mexico's Dept. of Health Secretary Kathy Kunkel has issued a public health order suspending gatherings of 100 or more people in a single space, solidifying the guidance Gov. Lujan Grisham gave yesterday regarding large events & ensuring that New Mexicans are prepared and proactive.

Right now public health is the first consideration. New Mexico is not going to wait as long as some other states to make hard decisions about this pandemic – the Governor is making sure we are doing everything we can to be ahead of the curve.

There are exemptions from the public health order – they include all educational institutions, airports and mass transit, malls and retail stores, shelters, offices and businesses, courthouses, child-care centers, health care facilities and other congregate care facilities, and places of worship.

Find more information here: http://bit.ly/2U1iulS

Stay updated with the dedicated COVID-19 website: https://cv.nmhealth.org

post_text:
Scholarship application due April 15

The Jesus Aguilar Memorial Scholarship was created for a Dexter High School student enrolled to attend a post secondary undergraduate degree granting school. The scholarship will be awarded in the amount of $1,000, renewable up to four years ($4,000 total). Scholarship award is eligible for expenses related to attaining their chosen bachelor’s degree
In order to apply for this scholarship, candidate must:
1. Be a senior enrolled at Dexter High School.
2. Be enrolled in or have been accepted to attend a post secondary undergraduate degree granting school.
3. Have maintained a grade point average of at least 2.0
4. Demonstrate financial need.
5. Complete an application and include a 500-750 word essay outlining the applicants future goals, plans for the use of the degree he/she intends to earn and the impact this scholarship would have in achieving those goals/plans.

Visit the link below for an application.

At the conclusion of each webinar, participants will be asked to complete a survey, and will receive a certificate of participation.

post_text: DHS alumnus, Marty Apodaca!
shared_text:
UNM - American Indian Student Services
October 2, 2019 at 12:00 PM ·

16 years ago, #AISSCampusPartner Marty Apodaca left his hometown of Dexter, NM to head for #LoboLand, where he’s earned a BA in English, and MA in Counseling. Currently, as a PhD student in Counselor Education, Marty’s expanding his #SAPro expertise to empower students to become the authors of their careers. One of the highlights of his role as a Career Development Facilitator with @unmcareerservices is being the Liaison to the #UNM Ethnic Centers and developing programming that best suits student needs. His most recent project “Managing Anxiety Around Career Uncertainty” is focused on helping students manage their concerns & doubts while better understanding the current professional arena. He’ll also be receiving his independent counseling licensure this month!! Marty’s contributed his insight & wisdom to the #AISS Ambassadors Program, Sidekicks, and the American Indian Summer Bridge Program & we’re enthusiastic about continuing our connection & collaboration with such a shining example of #LoboPride!! #UNMRoleModel #LobosMakingADifference

16 years ago, #AISSCampusPartner Marty Apodaca left his hometown of Dexter, NM to head for #LoboLand, where he’s earned a BA in English, and MA in Counseling. Currently, as a PhD student in Counselor Education, Marty’s expanding his #SAPro expertise to empower students to become the authors of their careers. One of the highlights of his role as a Career Development Facilitator with @unmcareerservices is being the Liaison to the #UNM Ethnic Centers and developing programming that best suits student needs. His most recent project “Managing Anxiety Around Career Uncertainty” is focused on helping students manage their concerns & doubts while better understanding the current professional arena. He’ll also be receiving his independent counseling licensure this month!! Marty’s contributed his insight & wisdom to the #AISS Ambassadors Program, Sidekicks, and the American Indian Summer Bridge Program & we’re enthusiastic about continuing our connection & collaboration with such a shining example of #LoboPride!! #UNMRoleModel #LobosMakingADifference

post_text:
Attention High School Parents, we have a few important announcements.
1. We are starting dual credit enrollment today. Please have all forms signed and returned to the front office on Friday.
2. Seniors who need to retest for graduation requirements will be retesting next week. Letters were mailed out yesterday to parents to let you know if your student needs to retest.
3. We will have academic Saturday school next Saturday, December 14th, 2019, from 8:00-11:00 AM. This will be the last stretch to improve grades before finals week. If your student is behind or failing a class, please have them attend this extra work time.
text:
Attention High School Parents, we have a few important announcements.
1. We are starting dual credit enrollment today. Please have all forms signed and returned to the front office on Friday.
2. Seniors who need to retest for graduation requirements will be retesting next week. Letters were mailed out yesterday to parents to let you know if your student needs to retest.
3. We will have academic Saturday school next Saturday, December 14th, 2019, from 8:00-11:00 AM. This will be the last stretch to improve grades before finals week. If your student is behind or failing a class, please have them attend this extra work time.
